Entire List of Messages for Objects

AICombatOpportunity
This object sets up an indirect combat action

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ENABLE Enable an AICombatOpportunity. msg CombatOpportunity ENABLE
DISABLE Disable an AICombatOpportunity. AICombatOpportunity may start disabled using the StartDisabled property flag in WorldEdit. msg CombatOpportunity DISABLE
ACTIVATE Activates an AICombatOpportunity. This causes the AICombatOpportunity to dispatch its' ActivateCommand, as well as shut down. AICombatOpporunities may only be activated a single time, and only while enabled. msg CombatOpportunity ACTIVATE


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
EnemyArea This will bring up a dialog where valid areas for the AIs enemy to be to use this CombatOpportunity may be entered. AICombatOpportunityRadius objects or AIRegions may be entered. If no object are listed, the AIs enemies position will be unconstrained. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
EnemyArea0 The name of an AICombatOpportunityRadius object or AIRegion the AI may use this CombatOpportunity from. String
EnemyArea1 The name of an AICombatOpportunityRadius object or AIRegion the AI may use this CombatOpportunity from. String
EnemyArea2 The name of an AICombatOpportunityRadius object or AIRegion the AI may use this CombatOpportunity from. String
EnemyArea3 The name of an AICombatOpportunityRadius object or AIRegion the AI may use this CombatOpportunity from. String

ActionNode This will bring up a dialog where you can enter the nodes which an AI may use to activate this AICombatOpportunity. If no nodes are specified, this CombatOpportunity will only be used by shooting at the object specified in the RangedTargetObject field. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ActionNode0 The name of a node the AI can use when he desires to activate this CombatOpportunity. Use of this node must (directly or indirectly) cause an ACTIVATE message to be sent to this CombatOpportunity object. String

ActionNode9 The name of a node the AI can use when he desires to activate this CombatOpportunity. Use of this node must (directly or indirectly) cause an ACTIVATE message to be sent to this CombatOpportunity object. String
ViewNodes This will bring up a dialog where you can enter the hints for the AI attempting to use this CombatOpportunity via a ranged weapon. If the AI does not have line of sight from its current position, it will look for AINodeCombatOpportunityView nodes the CombatOpportunity specifies. These nodes are locations where the AI will have line of sight to the CombatOpportunity. These nodes allow AI to proactively move to a location where it can shoot at the node. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
CombatOpportunityViewNode0 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode1 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode2 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode3 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String

CombatOpportunityViewNode5 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode6 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode7 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode8 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
CombatOpportunityViewNode9 The name of a node where the AI can move to when he cannot currently see the CombatOpportunity. String
RangedTargetObject The AI will perform visibility tests to the center point of this object to determine if this AICombatOpportunity is valid for ranged weapon use. If the AI can see it, it will then shoot at this object. If no object is specified, AIs will only attempt to use this CombatOpportunity through ActionNodes. String
ActivateCommand This command is dispatched when the AICombatOpportunity receives an ACTIVATE message. String
AllySound This AI sound is played by an ally to announce an AI firing at this combat opportunity. String (StaticList) None
StartDisabled If true the AICombatOpportunity will begin disabled. Boolean 0.000000

AINode
This is the most basic node type. The only purpose of a basic AINode is as a destination for a Goto command

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE TODO:CMDDESC TODO:CMDEXP
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ENABLE Enable an AINode. msg AINode01 enable
DISABLE Disable an AINode. Nodes may start disabled using the StartDisabled property flag in WorldEdit. msg AINode01 disable


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Face Set this to true if you want the AI who uses this node to face along the forward of the node. Boolean 1.000000
FacingOffset Offset AI should face from the node's rotation. Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
CharacterType This is a dropdown list that allows you to set the character type restriction for the AINode. Only AI that are of the character type are able to use the node. String (StaticList) None
StartDisabled If true the AINode will begin disabled. Boolean 0.000000

Camera
This object allows you to setup a cinematic camera.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON Turns the camera on. Switches the view from the player to that of the camera msg Camera on
OFF Turns the camera off. Switches the view from the Camera to that of the Player msg Camera off
SKIP Turns the camera off if it can be skipped msg Camera skip
MOVETO <camerapoint> The camera will move to the specified CameraPoint object msg Camera (moveto CameraPoint1)
FOV <FovY> <FovAspectScale> [time] Changes the Camera FOV over a period of time. The time parameter is optional To change the camera FOV to an Y FOV of 60 and a normal 1.0 Aspect Scale over a period of five seconds on a Camera named "Camera", the command would look like:

msg Camera (60 1 5)


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
ActiveTime If you want a camera to return to the player after a set period, give the camera a time-limit property. Float -1.000000
AllowPlayerMovement Choose whether the player can move or not while the camera's running. Obviously, in most cases the camera should keep players still. Boolean 0.000000
OneTime Keeps the camera from being activated after it's been run once, even if it's triggered again. Boolean 1.000000
Type There are two types of camera: full-screen = 0 and cinematic letterboxed = 1. Integer 1.000000
StartActive Allows you to have the camera start when the level starts for an intro cutscene. Boolean 0.000000
IsListener If you want the camera to relay sounds it hears to the player instead of the sounds at the player's location, use this flag. Boolean 1.000000
CanSkip If set to true, the player can interrupt the cinematic by pressing the action key in the game. If this flag is set to false, the cinematic cannot be interrupted. Boolean 1.000000
CleanupCommand A command that will be executed when the Camera is turned off, either by a message or by the player skipping it. Command
FovY The starting Field Of View Y value. Note: You can dynamicly change the FovY and AspectScale values of a camera by sending it an FOV message. Float 78.000000
FovAspectScale The starting Field Of View Aspect Scale value. This value is used for special effects to warp the field of view in the X direction. >1 will cause the view to grow outwards, <1 will shrink the FOV in the X direction. Note: You can dynamicly change the FovY and Aspect Scale values of a camera by sending it an FOV message. Float 1.000000
OnSkipCleanupOnly If set to true, only the CleanupCommand will be sent if the player skips the cinematic. The camera will be able to be activated again even if OneTime is set to true. Boolean 0.000000

CommandObject
The CommandObject is a multitrack command manager that allows for the manipulation and execution of multiple commands on a timeline.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)

ON Tells the CommandObject to begin running its time line and sending its commands msg CommandObject ON
OFF Tells the CommandObject to stop running its time line and sends no more commands msg CommandObject OFF
PAUSE Tells the CommandObject to pause its time and halt sending the commands until it is resumed. msg CommandObject PAUSE
RESUME Tells the CommandObject to resume its time from a pause and continue sending its commands. msg CommandObject RESUME
LOCK Locks the CommandObject so that it ignores all commands other than UNLOCK and REMOVE msg CommandObject LOCK
UNLOCK unlocks the CommandObject msg CommandObject UNLOCK

Controller
This object enables controlled WorldModels to perform fade functions.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
FADE <parameter type> <destination value> <duration> <wave type><BR><BR>The default wave type is sine Fades a parameter between two values over a specified period of time.

Supported parameter types are:

Alpha value 0 to 1
Color values 0 to 255.

Must be specified in quotes. If you specify an X value, that value will not be changed.

Supported wave types are:

LINEAR
SINE
SLOWOFF
SLOWON		 To fade alpha to 0 over 5 seconds the command would look like:

msg Controller (fade alpha 0 5 sine)

To fade color to 0 128 255 over 7 seconds using a slowon wave the command would look like:

msg Controller (fade color "0 128 255" 7 slowon)
OFF Stops whatever the controller is doing msg Controller off

CorrosiveFluid

Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname

Visible Determines if this object is visible by default Boolean 0.000000
Hidden This flag allows you to make a volume begin hidden in the level. Later you can send a (hidden 0) message to the VolumeBrush object to unhide it. Boolean 0.000000
Friction This property allows you to alter the friction coefficient of surfaces to create slippery surfaces. Float 1.000000
Current This is a force that pushes against the player. Use positive or negative values along each axis (x, y, and z) to indicate the direction and strength of the current. In general, you'll need values in the thousands in order to lift a player off the ground. This works well to create moving streams or areas of rushing wind. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
LightAdd This allows you to further alter the view from inside a Volume. Color 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
CanPlayMovementSounds This flag disables the footstep sounds and head-bob motion in a volume. Boolean 1.000000
FogStuff This is a subset of properties that define the fog effects that will be seen when the player is within the Volume Brush. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
FogEnable This flag toggles the fog effects on and off. Boolean 0.000000
FogFarZ This is a value that determines at what distance the fog reaches full saturation. Float 300.000000
FogNearZ This value determines at what distance the fog is at zero saturation. Float -100.000000
FogColor This color picker determines the color of the fog effect. Color 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
ForceVolumeProps This is a subset of properties that define the physics force volume that can be associated with this volume to control how rigid bodies are affected in this volume Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ForceVolume Determines if this volume brush should have a force volume associated with it or not Boolean 0.000000
ForceDir This specifies the direction of the constant force in the volume, relative to the volume Rotation 270.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
ForceMag This specifies the strength of the constant force, and can range from 0 to +inf Float 100.000000
ForceWaveFreq This is used to control the fluctuation of the constant force, and describes how many times per second the force will cycle between +1 and -1. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 0.500000
ForceWaveAmp This is used to control the how much the fluctuation of the wave influences the scale of the force. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
ForceWaveBaseOffset The is used to control the base offset for the wave fluctuation of the scale. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
Density This is used to specify the density of the volume. Setting this to zero will disable buoyancy, anything else will cause the volume to apply a force based upon how dense this liquid is and how large the objects inside of it are. This is in g/cm^3. The density of water is 1 g/cm^3 Float 1.000000
LinearDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it moves through the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.002000
AngularDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it rotates in the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.300000
SurfaceFlagsOverride This dropdown menu allows you to choose a specific surface flag for the VolumeBrush. NOTE: If the Unknown surface flag is used, the surface flag of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Unknown
RayHit This flag toggles whether or not the object will be rayhit. Boolean 0.000000
StartOn This flag toggles whether or not the volume will be considered ON when the level first loads. Boolean 1.000000
Resistance This value affects the resistance of the players movement through the volume. Float 0.080000
Damage Sets amount of damage dealt by this area for every second the player is in it. Float 5.000000
SoundFilter You could have sound behave differently inside the volume. In the case of liquid, you could mute out high frequencies. In the case of a dimensional gate, you might add a strange echo or other filter. String (StaticList) Underwater
TintColor You can define a tint for the player's view if you want the area to look as if it's filled with light or liquid. Color 76.500000, 102.000000, 0.000000
AllowSwimming If true, players will be allowed to swim in the volume. If false, players will not play their swimming animations. Boolean 1.000000
SurfaceOverride This dropdown menu allows you to choose a specific surface type for the VolumeBrush. NOTE: If the Unknown surface type is used, the surface type of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Liquid

FogColor This color picker determines the color of the fog effect. Color 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
LinearDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it moves through the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.002000
AngularDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it rotates in the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.300000
SurfaceFlagsOverride This dropdown menu allows you to choose a specific surface flag for the VolumeBrush. NOTE: If the Unknown surface flag is used, the surface flag of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Unknown
RayHit This flag toggles whether or not the object will be rayhit. Boolean 0.000000
StartOn This flag toggles whether or not the volume will be considered ON when the level first loads. Boolean 1.000000
Damage Sets amount of damage dealt by this area for every second the player is in it. Float 20.000000

EventCounter
The EventCounter object is used to send certain commands for specific values of the event counter. The value of the EventCounter is initialy set through the StartingValue property and then controlled using the INC and DEC messages.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
INC <amount> Adds the specified amount to the current value of the EventCounter object msg EventCounter (INC 1)
DEC <amount> Subtracts the specified amount from the current value of the EventCounter object msg EventCounter (DEC 1)
LOCK Locks the EventCounter so that it ignores all commands other than UNLOCK and REMOVE msg EventCounter LOCK
UNLOCK Unlocks the EventCounter msg EventCounter UNLOCK


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname

Explosion
Explosion objects are used to create a dynamic explosion with a ClientFX, damage type and physics impulse force.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON Turns the explosion on. msg Explosion ON


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
ImpactFXName Select from a list of ImpactFX listed in GameDatabase under FX\ImpactFX. String (StaticList)
DamageType This is a pull down used to identify what kind of damage will be inflicted upon anyone caught within the DamageRadius of the Explosion object when it is triggered. String (StaticList) EXPLODE
DamageRadiusMin This the minimum radius measured in WorldEdit units in which an object will take 100% of the MaxDamage damage from the explosion. The damage amount is linearly scaled from MaxDamage to 0 between the DamageRadiusMin and DamageRadius. NOTE: If set to 0, 25% of the DamageRadius will be used for the DamageRadiusMin. Float (Radius) 0.000000
DamageRadius This the radius measured in WorldEdit units in which an object will take damage from the explosion. Float (Radius) 200.000000
MaxDamage This field defines the maximum amount of damage that will be inflicted upon an object caught within the DamageRadius of the explosion when it is triggered. Float 200.000000
RemoveWhenDone This flag toggles whether or not the explosion is removed after being triggered. Sometimes you will want to trigger an Explosion object repeatedly. In which case you would set this flag to false. Boolean 1.000000
ImpulseForce The amount of force the explosion will apply to objects inside the DamageRadiusMin. The force is linearly scaled between ImpulseForce and 0 between DamageRadiusMin and DamageRadius. The value is measured in game unit newton seconds. Float 5000.000000

Flicker
An object that will generate random intensities convert these into messages that can be sent off to objects for tasks such as flickering lights or world models

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)

CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON Tells the specified flicker object to be able to begin flickering msg Flicker ON
OFF Tells the specified flicker object to stop flickering and restore default alpha values to the objects msg Flicker OFF
LOCK Tells the specified flicker object to stop sending any scale alpha commands to other objects. It will still update normally and recieve messages, it will just not change the intensity of other objects msg Flicker LOCK
UNLOCK Tells the specified flicker object to resume normal sending of messages to objects (See LOCK for more information) msg Flicker UNLOCK

FlickerMin Indicates the minimum value that can be used for a flicker value. This should be within the range of [0..1] and less than the maximum. Float 0.000000
FlickerMax Indicates the maximum value that can be used for a flicker value. This should be within the range of [0..1] and more than the minimum. Float 1.000000
FlickerWave Indicates the wave form that will be used to control the flickering scale. This will scale the flicker min and max. String (StaticList) None
FlickerWavePeriod Indicates how often the wave repeats. Higher values cause the transition to be slower. Float 10.000000
FrequencyMin Indicates the minimum amount of time in seconds that will be elapsed before a new flicker value is determined. This should be less than the frequency maximum Float 0.000000
FrequencyMax Indicates the maximum amount of time in seconds that will be elapsed before a new flicker value is determined. This should be more than the frequency minimum Float 0.000000

StartOn Indicates whether or not this flicker object should start in an enabled state or not Boolean 1.000000

ForceDir This specifies the direction of the constant force in the volume, relative to the volume Rotation 270.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000

ForceWaveFreq This is used to control the fluctuation of the constant force, and describes how many times per second the force will cycle between +1 and -1. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 0.500000
ForceWaveAmp This is used to control the how much the fluctuation of the wave influences the scale of the force. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
ForceWaveBaseOffset The is used to control the base offset for the wave fluctuation of the scale. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
Density This is used to specify the density of the volume. Setting this to zero will disable buoyancy, anything else will cause the volume to apply a force based upon how dense this liquid is and how large the objects inside of it are. This is in g/cm^3. The density of water is 1 g/cm^3 Float 1.000000

Key
Key objects are used in conjunction with the KeyFramer object to create KeyFramed paths for objects to follow.

Message Description Example


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
TimeStamp This is the time that it takes for the KeyFramer to get to this key from the previous key in the key path. Float 0.000000
SoundName The name of the sound record that will be played when the KeyFramer arrives at this Key on the key path. String (StaticList)
Command This is a Command string that that will be processed when the KeyFramer arrives at this key. Command
BezierPrev When making a key path it is possible to create Bezier Curves. While in Object mode, if you select one of the Keys in a key path, press the P key and drag the mouse while pressing the LMB, you will pull out the Bezier handle on the 'in' side of the key. This field denotes the world coordinate position of that handle. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
BezierNext After pulling out the first Bewzier handle, you can repeat the process to pull out the bezier handle on the 'out' side of the key. This field denotes the world coordinate position of that handle. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000



KeyFramer
The keyframer is a class that will move the specified objects along a path and can trigger sounds and commands as it moves. The path is specified using either key objects or a path stored in an external key file. The movement rate can either be specified using key times, or can use the distance between keys if TotalPathTime is set to non-zero, in which case it will traverse the full path in that specified amount of time.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON Tells the KeyFramer to start moving its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys starting on the 0 key msg KeyFramer ON
OFF Tells the KeyFramer to stop moving its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys. The objects stop wherever they are on the path msg KeyFramer OFF
PAUSE Tells the KeyFramer to pause the movement of its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys msg KeyFramer PAUSE
RESUME Tells the KeyFramer to pause the movement of its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys msg KeyFramer RESUME
FORWARD Tells the KeyFramer to move its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys in a forward direction msg KeyFramer FORWARD
REVERSE Tells the KeyFramer to move its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys in a backward direction msg KeyFramer REVERSE
TOGGLEDIR Tells the KeyFramer to move its listed objects along the path defined by its specified keys in the opposite direction it is currently traveling in msg KeyFramer TOGGLEDIR
GOTO <key> Tells the KeyFramer to immediately move its listed objects to a specific Key along the path defined by its specified keys To tell a set of objects Keyframed by a KeyFramer named "KeyFramer" to goto a specific Key named Key03 the command would look like:

msg KeyFramer (GOTO Key03)
MOVETO <key> [destination cmd] Tells the KeyFramer to move its listed objects to a specific Key along the path defined by its specified keys by traveling the path to that specific Key. It will also send the command listed in the optional destion cmd paramater To tell a set of objects Keyframed by a KeyFramer named "KeyFramer" to move to a specific Key named Key03 the command would look like:

msg KeyFramer (MOVETO Key03)
TARGET <object> Tells the KeyFramer to rotate the Z vector of its listed object toward a specific target object To tell a set of objects Keyframed by a KeyFramer named "KeyFramer" to face the player the command would look like:

msg KeyFramer (TARGET player)
CLEARTARGET Tells the KeyFramer to stop aligning the Z vector of its specified objects to face a specified target msg KeyFramer CLEARTARGET
TARGETOFFSET <x> <y> <z> If a target name is specified, KeyFramed objects will always face the targeted objects position plus the offset specified in the target offset parameter To tell a set of objects Keyframed by a KeyFramer named "KeyFramer" that is targeting the player to maintain an offset 5, 5, and 10 the command would look like:

msg KeyFramer (TARGETOFFSET 5 5 10)


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
ObjectName This feild contains the name of the object or worldmodel that is to be affected by the keyframer. This feild can contain the names of several objects and/or worldmodels seperated by semicolons. String
Interpolation This indicates how movement between keys will be handled. Linear is much cheaper but doesn't look as smooth for a small number of keys. Bezier is more expensive but smoother and requires tangents. String (StaticList) Linear
BaseKeyName The base name of the keys that the KeyFramer object will follow. The first key must be named with the base name followed by 0. All subsequent keys must be named with the base name followed by two-digit increments. For example, if the BaseKeyName was 'Base', the keys would be named Base0, Base01, Base02, Base03, etc. String
ExternalKeyFile If your animation keys are in a separate .Key00c file, exported from max, enter the file path of your animations here. The KeyFramer will then look at the file for the keys. String
PushObjects Determines whether or not the KeyFramer will push objects in the world. Boolean 0.000000
StartActive If set to true, the KeyFramer will begin active. Boolean 0.000000
StartPaused This flag works in conjunction with the StartActive flag. This flag will tell the KeyFramer to begin in the paused state if active. Boolean 0.000000
Looping If set to true the keyframer will continuously run through the key path, returning to the first key in the sequence when reaching the last. Boolean 0.000000
MaintainOffsets Tells the KeyFramer whether or not to maintain offsets of position and rotation between the object being keyframed and the keys that make up the path. If set to false, the keyframed object will acquire the exact position and rotation of the keys that make up the key path. Boolean 1.000000
TargetName You can specify a prop, worldmodel, or model in this field. The KeyFramer will attempt to continually point it's forward facing vector at this object as it travels along its key path. String
TargetOffset You may enter a target offset in this field. It is entered in the form of x,y,z offset in WorldEdit units. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
ActiveSound The name of a sound record that will be played while the KeyFramer object is active. String (StaticList)
Waveform The WaveForm flag is a subset of properties that define the movement characteristics of the KeyFramer object. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
TotalPathTime This is the approximate time in seconds that it will take for the KeyFramer object to complete it's travel down the key path. Note that by specifying this, it will ignore the time stamps of the keys and instead use the distance between the keys as the primary factor Float 0.000000
Wavetype This is a dropdown list of different Waves that the KeyFramer can use while following it's path. The KeyFramer will vary it's velocity depending on the wave type chosen. Note that this is only used if the TotalPathTime is non-zero, otherwise it is ignored String (StaticList) Linear
GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000



KeyframeToRigidBody
KeyframeToRigidBody objects are used to turn multiple objects at once to rigid body when it receives the ON message. On the next frame of processing (after a physics update has occured) the command specified will then be sent.

SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)

msg Trigger (LOCK LookAt);
msg Trigger (LOCK LookAway);

msg Trigger (UNLOCK LookAt);
msg Trigger (UNLOCK LookAway);
LOOKAT Sets the object to its LookAt state, ignoring threshold, executing the LookAt command and incrementing the number of lookats msg Trigger LOOKAT;
LOOKAWAY Sets the object to its LookAway state, ignoring threshold, executing the LookAway msg Trigger LOOKAWAY;

Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname

ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Dims The dimensions of the trigger in the game. If the player has to walk into the trigger to fire it, you should set the dimensions. If the trigger is fired off by another object, then they don't need to be changed. Trigger dimensions are set as x, y and z values. You can make each of them as small as 0 or as large as you need. For example, for a trigger that fills a typical doorway you would set the dims to 128 128 4. Using the 4 is just to make the object easier to find. Triggers can be any size. Vector (Dims) 16.000000, 16.000000, 16.000000
NumberOfActivations This value sets how many times the Trigger object can be activated. Setting this value to 0 allows the Trigger to be activated an infinite number of times. Integer 1.000000
SendDelay A specified amount of seconds between the time the Trigger object receives a trigger message, and the when it sends its command strings. Float 0.000000
TriggerDelay After being triggered, this is the amount of time before the Trigger object can be activated again. Float 0.000000
Commands This is a subset of properties that are command strings the trigger object will process when triggered. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
Command1 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command2 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command3 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command

Command6 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command

Command8 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command9 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command10 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
TimedTrigger If this flag is set to true the Trigger object will continue to send its messages repeatedly based on the minimum and maximum times set in the MinTriggerTime and MaxTriggerTime fields. Boolean 0.000000
MinTriggerTime If the trigger's TimedTrigger flag is set to true, this value will set the shortest delay before the trigger fires. Float 0.000000
MaxTriggerTime If the trigger's TimedTrigger flag is set to true, this value will set the longest delay before the trigger fires. Float 10.000000
ActivationCount This field is used to set an activation threshold. The Trigger object will need to receive a number of 'trigger' messages equal to the value entered in this field before its messages will be sent. Integer 1.000000
Locked This property can be used if you only want to be able to trip the trigger after a certain event has happened. You would also need a Condition variable, or Unlock messages on the objects that can unlock the trigger. Boolean 0.000000
ActivationSound Specifies a sound file to play when the trigger fires. If you want a player to know that they've just set something off, found a clue or entered a cut scene, this can be useful. String (Filename)
SoundRadius Determines the distance from the trigger that you can hear the ActivationSound play, if it has one. Float (Radius) 200.000000
AttachToObject Attaches a Trigger to an object, such as a Prop or a WorldModel. If the object moves, so does the trigger. String
HUDLookAtDist If this is greater than 0, a HUD icon indicating that the player is close to the trigger will appear when the player is looking at the trigger and is this distancs away from the dims of the object. Float (Radius) -1.000000
HUDAlwaysOnDist If this is greater than 0, a HUD icon indicating that the player is close to the trigger will appear when the player is this distance away form the center of the object. Float (Radius) -1.000000
TriggerType A dropdown list of 'TriggerTypes' from TriggerTypes.txt. Selecting a TriggerType will display the icon specified in the text file when the player is within the HUDLookAtDist and HUDAlwaysOnDist. Selecting will display no icon. String (StaticList)



ObjectRemover
Remove groups of objects when level starts. If the number of GroupsToKeep is less than the number of groups defined then the groups removed will be chosen and random.

PhysicsImpulseDirectional
The PhysicsImpulseDirectional object should be used to apply a physical force the physically simulated objects specifed. These objects will receive ImpulseForce amount of force applied in the direction specified by the foward vector of this PhysicsImpulseDirectional object. The force value is measured in game unit newton seconds.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)

MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)

PhysicsImpulseRadial
The PhysicsImpulseRadial object should be used to apply a physical force in a sphere around the position of the object. All physically simulated objects within RadiusMin distance from the PhysicsImpulseRadial object will have ImpulseForce amount of force applied to them in the direction determined by the vector from the center of the PhysicsImpulseRadial object to the center of the physically simulated object. The force applied to physically simulated objects outside of RadiusMin but inside RadiusMax is linearly scaled between ImpulseForce and 0 between RadiusMin and RadiusMax. The force value is measured in game unit newton seconds.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON Trigger the object to apply the specified impulse force. msg PhysicsImpulseRadial ON


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
ImpulseForce The amount of force the PhysicsImpulseRadial object will apply to objects inside the RadiusMin. This force value is linearly scaled between ImpulseForce and 0 between RadiusMin and RadiusMax. The value is measured in game unit newton seconds. Float 5000.000000
RadiusMin This the minimum radius measured in WorldEdit units from the center of the PhysicsImpulseRadial object in which 100% of the impulse force will be applied to objects. The force amount is linearly scaled from ImpulseForce to 0 between the RadiusMin and RadiusMax. Float (Radius) 50.000000
RadiusMax This the maximum radius measured in WorldEdit units from the center of the PhysicsImpulseRadial object in which the impulse force will be applied to objects. The force amount is linearly scaled from ImpulseForce to 0 between the RadiusMin and RadiusMax. Float (Radius) 200.000000
RemoveWhenDone This flag toggles whether or not the PhysicsImpulseRadial object is removed after being triggered. Sometimes you will want to trigger an PhysicsImpulseRadial object repeatedly. In which case you would set this flag to false. Boolean 1.000000

Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname

LimitedYawLeftRight Specifies camera rotation to left and right of center that is allowed. Separate left and right value with a space. Setting left < -180 and right > 180 means unlimited yaw. String -360 360

Dims The dimensions of the trigger in the game. If the player has to walk into the trigger to fire it, you should set the dimensions. If the trigger is fired off by another object, then they don't need to be changed. Trigger dimensions are set as x, y and z values. You can make each of them as small as 0 or as large as you need. For example, for a trigger that fills a typical doorway you would set the dims to 128 128 4. Using the 4 is just to make the object easier to find. Triggers can be any size. Vector (Dims) 16.000000, 16.000000, 16.000000

PolyGrid
Class that simulates the surface of a body of water. If used with a liquid volume brush make sure the top of the volume brush is at the same Y value as the polygrid object if you want bullet vectors to perturb the surface of the water.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)

ON <Modifier> Turns a PolyGridModifier object specified in the WavePropInfo property of the PolyGrid on. The command is targeted at the Modifier number To turn on the PolyGridModifier specified in the Modifier1 property field of a PolyGrid named "PolyGrid" the command would look like:

msg PolyGrid (ON 1)
OFF <Modifier> Turns a PolyGridModifier object specified in the WavePropInfo property of the PolyGrid off. The command is targeted at the Modifier number To turn off the PolyGridModifier specified in the Modifier1 property field of a PolyGrid named "PolyGrid" the command would look like:

msg PolyGrid (OFF 1)


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000

IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Dims Determines the size of the grid. Polygrids normally face up (Y axis), so a typical polygrid Dims setting would be 256 8 256, for a thin grid that fills a large hole in a floor. Vector (Dims LocalDims) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Color Specifies the color of the polygrid Color 255.000000, 255.000000, 255.000000
Material The material that will be used to render this polygrid String (Filename)
TextureInfo Information describing how the texturing is applied to the polygrid surface Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
XScaleMin Specifies the minimum scale that the texture used on the PolyGrid will scale to. This allows you to have the texture on the PolyGrid swim up and down in size. The number represents the number of units over which a texture will repeat Float 100.000000
XScaleMax See XScaleMin. Float 100.000000
YScaleMin Specifies the maximum texture scale on the PolyGrid. See XScaleMin. Float 100.000000
YScaleMax See XscaleMax. Float 100.000000
XScaleDuration Determines the length of time the PolyGrid will take to scale between XScaleMin and XScaleMax. Float 10.000000
YScaleDuration See XScaleDuration. Float 10.000000
XPan If the PolyGrid is textured, you can enter a panning speed here to have the texture pan along the PolyGrid's X-axis. Speed is in game units/second. Typical values would be from 20 to 20 for fairly fast speed and 5 to 5 for slow. Float 10.000000
YPan See XPan. Float 10.000000
Alpha The translucency of the grid as a whole. If you want to use a texture without an alpha mask or fine-tune the alpha for a texture that does have an alpha mask, this is a useful property. A value of 1 is fully opaque, .5 is half-translucent and 0 is transparent. Float 0.700000
RenderSolid Determines if this polygrid should be rendered as a solid or translucent object Boolean 0.000000
NumPoliesX The number of segments the polygrid will have along the X direction. The higher the number of polies you add, the smoother the grid will look, but it will also take longer to render. Integer 16.000000
NumPoliesY The number of segments the polygrid will have along the Y direction. The higher the number of polies you add, the smoother the grid will look, but it will also take longer to render. Integer 16.000000
MinResolutionScale A value in the range of [0..1] that indicates the minimum scale that can be used for the resolution of the polygrid. 0 allows it to go down to 2x2, 1 prevents the resolution from changing with LOD, 0.5 allows dropping of 50% resolution at lowest LOD, etc. Float 0.000000
WavePropInfo Properties that control how the surface of the water moves Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
TimeScale A multiplier used to speed up time on the surface which causes waves to move up and down faster. Float 1.000000
DampenScale A multiplier used to remove energy from the system. So if it was .95, it would use 95% of the previous energy, allowing 5% to dissappear, this prevents water simulations from exploding. Float 0.990000
SpringCoeff Coefficient for the rigidness of the water springs. Raising this value will cause the water to move back into place faster, and lower will make it look more viscous. Float 40.000000
ModelDisplace Specifies how much a model moving through the surface should displace. Higher values will create higher waves. Float 10.000000
MinFrameRate The minimum frame rate that the polygrid can run at. If the frame rate drops below this the polygrid will just pretent it is running at this frame rate Float 10.000000
NumStartupFrames This indicates how many frames will be simulated when the polygrid is created. This helps prevent a completely flat surface when a level is loaded Integer 0.000000
Modifier1 Name of a modifier that will affect the surface. String
Modifier2 Name of a modifier that will affect the surface. String
Modifier3 Name of a modifier that will affect the surface. String
Modifier4 Name of a modifier that will affect the surface. String

ReflectionMap Create a reflection map render target, bound to the tReflectionMap parameter of the material Boolean 0.000000
ReflectionMapLOD Indicates at which this reflection map LOD. For low, it will always be visible, for medium, it will only be visible in medium or higher and so on. Never disables this map. String (StaticList) Low
ReflectionMapRTGroup The render target group that the reflection map should use. Note that this should not be the same as the refraction map, and is not needed if the reflection is disabled String
RefractionMap Create a refraction map render target, bound to the tRefractionMap parameter of the material Boolean 0.000000
RefractionMapLOD Indicates at which this refraction map LOD. For low, it will always be visible, for medium, it will only be visible in medium or higher and so on. Never disables this map. String (StaticList) Low

RotatingDoor
A RotatingDoor is a Door object that rotates around a specified point.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ATTACH <object name(s)> Attaches the object specified in the message

If no object is specified it attaches the first object found in the direction of the AttachDir vector or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0>		 To attach a WorldModel named BOX to a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg Ball (attach box)
DETACH <object name(s)> Detach a specific object attached with the ATTACH message. To detach a WorldModel named BOX from a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg BALL (DETACH BOX)
ATTACHCLASS <class name> This will attach the first object of the specified class found in the direction of AttachDir or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0> To attach any AI to the WorldModel the command would look like:

msg WorldModel (ATTACHCLASS CAI)
DESTROY This command destroys an object in the game as if it had been destroyed trough the loss of all of its hit points. It will play any effects and sounds set up to play at the time of its destruction msg WorldModel DESTROY
NEVERDESTROY <1 or 0> This message allows you to set the NeverDestroy flag through commands. This message does not actually destroy the object but allows destruction if NeverDestroy was set to true initially. msg WorldModel (NEVERDESTROY 1)
ACTIVATE This is an internal message used strictly by the game to activate a WorldModel. Do NOT send any WorldModel an ACTIVATE message. DO NOT USE
RIGIDBODY <bool> This command will set the RigidBody flag on the object making it physically simulated (1) or not (0) msg WorldModel RIGIDBODY 1
SCALEALPHA <0..1> This command will scale the alpha of this world model by the specified value as long as it is flagged as being translucent msg WorldModel ScaleAlpha 0.7
TOGGLE Toggles the ON / OFF state of the WorldModel. msg WorldModel01 TOGGLE;
LOCK Locks the WorldModel. A locked WorldModel may not be activated by a message or by the player. msg WorldModel01 LOCK;
UNLOCK Unlocks the WorldModel so it may be activated through messages or by the player. msg WorldModel01 UNLOCK;
PAUSE Pauses the WorldModel while moving or rotating. Sending a PAUSE message to a WorldModel while is is in the ON or OFF state has no effect. Send a RESUME message to continue the movement or rotation. msg WorldModel01 PAUSE;
RESUME Resumes the movement or rotation from a paused WorldModel. Sending a RESUME message to a WorldModel while it is not paused has no effect. msg WorldModel01 RESUME;
SETPOWERONMULTIPLIER <multiplyer> Setting a power on multiplyer will temporairly increase or decrease the speed at which the WorldModel turns on. This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

Boolean 1.000000

Commands This is a subset that lets you write commands for specific states that the object will cary out when in that state. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ActivateAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is activated. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
RotateAroundCenter When set to TRUE, object will use the center of worldmodel geometry as rotation point. When sent to FALSE, object will use WorldModel object as rotation point. If RotationPoint is specified, this property is ignored. Boolean 0.000000
PowerOffTime If other than 0.0, sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the On state to the off state. If this is 0.0 then the PowerOnTime value is used. Float 0.000000
PowerOffRadius If other than 0.0, sets the minimum distance in centimeters from the WorldModels's power off position that ALL characters must be for the WorldModel to power off. Float 0.000000
Mass This value sets the mass of the object within the game. Float 10000.000000
NeverDestroy Toggles whether the object can be destroyed. Boolean 1.000000
PlayerActivate If TRUE the player can directly interact with this object by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
AIActivate If TRUE this lets the AI know they can interact with this object. When FALSE the AI will treat the object like it doesn't exist. Boolean 1.000000
StartOpen When set to true the Door will be opening as soon as the game loads. Boolean 0.000000
TriggerClose If this is set to FALSE the player can not directly close the Door by pressing use. The Door can however be closed by a message from another object like a switch. If set to TRUE the player can directly close the Door by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
RemainOpen If set to FALSE the Door will try to start closing as soon as it becomes fully open. If TRUE the Door will stay open untill told to close, either by the player or a message from another object. Boolean 1.000000
ForceMove If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
Locked When set to TRUE the object starts in a Locked state. It can't be activated or triggered by a message unless it is unlocked. To unlock an object send it an UNLOCK message. To lock it again send a LOCK message. Boolean 0.000000
OpenAway If set to TRUE the RotatingDoor will open away from the player or AI that activated it. Boolean 1.000000
Waveform A list of predefined wave types for movement. Linear is a constant rate, objects will move at the same rate throught its whole path or rotation. SlowOn means the object starts moving slowly then picks up pace and will then stay constant. SlowOff will move constantly at first but will slow down at the end of the movement or rotation. Sine starts and ends slowly but looks very smooth and natural. String (StaticList) Linear
OpeningSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door starts opening. String (Filename)
OpenSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door is fully opened. String (Filename)
ClosingSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door starts closing. String (Filename)
ClosedSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object is fully closed. String (Filename)
LockedSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this sound will begin to play. String (Filename)
SoundPos The position that the sounds will be played from, relative to the objects position. If this is (0.0 0.0 0.0) the sounds will play at the center of the object, (0.0 25.0 0.0) will place the sounds 25 units above the objects center. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
SoundRadius This is the extent of the sounds, they will not be heard beyond this distance from the SoundPos. Float (Radius) 1000.000000
LoopSounds When set to TRUE, the sounds will comtinue to loop untill they change state. When FALSE the sounds will play their full length once and will then be destroyed. Boolean 0.000000
OpenCommand A command that this Door will execute when it is fully open. Command
ClosedCommand A command that this Door will execue when it is fully closed. Command
OpeningCommand A command that this Door will execute when starting to open. Command
ClosingCommand A command that this Door will execute when starting to close. Command
LockedCommand If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this command will be executed. Command
RotationPoint The name of a Point object which this WorldModel will rotate around. If no valid object name is given the WorldModel will rotate around the position of the bound object. String
RotationAngles These represent how far the WorldModel will rotate around the RotationPoint in the specified axi when turned on. (0.0 90.0 0.0) will rotate the WorldModel about the RotationPoint 90 degrees around the WorldModels local Y axis. Vector 0.000000, 90.000000, 0.000000
StartingAngles Specifes an optional initial rotation of the WorldModel. These are in degrees relative to the rotation of the WorldModel when in the off state. A StartingAngle of (0.0, 15.0, 0.0) will load the WorldModel with a rotation of 15 degrees around the WorldModels' local Y axis in the on direction. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
OpeningTime Sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the Off state to the on state. Float 1.000000
ClosingTime If other than 0.0, sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the On state to the off state. If this is 0.0 then the OpeningTime value is used. Float 0.000000
MoveDelay Amount of delay in seconds between the time the WorldModel is triggered and when it begins its movement. Float 0.000000
OpenWaitTime Amount of time in seconds that the Door will remain open before automatically closing, and the amount of time before the Door can be triggered again. Float 0.000000
CloseWaitTime Amount of time in secomds before the Door can be opened after being closed. Float 0.000000
DoorLink Use this to link two Doors together that you would like to open at the same time (i.e., Door1's DoorLink would be Door2, and Door2's DoorLink would be Door1). NOTE--Only the opening of linked doors is supported. Each door may be closed individually. String
Sector1 The brush name of a sector that will be turned on and off by this door as it opens and closes. String
Sector2 The brush name of a sector that will be turned on and off by this door as it opens and closes. String
BoxPhysics In the engine, WorldModels have two possible physics models. In the first, the player can walk on and touch every curve and corner of their surface. In the second, the player can only interact with a bounding box that surrounds all the brushes in the WorldModel, just like the box you would get if you selected them in WorldEdit. For geometry with a simple rectangular shape, this is preferred because it's cheaper to calculate. However, for a lot of objects, it's limiting. If you need a player to be able to shoot through the bars in a prison door, you will need BoxPhysics set to FALSE. Boolean 0.000000
GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000



RotatingSwitch
A RotatingSwitch is a Switch object that rotates around a specified point.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ATTACH <object name(s)> Attaches the object specified in the message

If no object is specified it attaches the first object found in the direction of the AttachDir vector or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0>		 To attach a WorldModel named BOX to a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg Ball (attach box)
DETACH <object name(s)> Detach a specific object attached with the ATTACH message. To detach a WorldModel named BOX from a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg BALL (DETACH BOX)
ATTACHCLASS <class name> This will attach the first object of the specified class found in the direction of AttachDir or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0> To attach any AI to the WorldModel the command would look like:

msg WorldModel (ATTACHCLASS CAI)
DESTROY This command destroys an object in the game as if it had been destroyed trough the loss of all of its hit points. It will play any effects and sounds set up to play at the time of its destruction msg WorldModel DESTROY
NEVERDESTROY <1 or 0> This message allows you to set the NeverDestroy flag through commands. This message does not actually destroy the object but allows destruction if NeverDestroy was set to true initially. msg WorldModel (NEVERDESTROY 1)
ACTIVATE This is an internal message used strictly by the game to activate a WorldModel. Do NOT send any WorldModel an ACTIVATE message. DO NOT USE
RIGIDBODY <bool> This command will set the RigidBody flag on the object making it physically simulated (1) or not (0) msg WorldModel RIGIDBODY 1
SCALEALPHA <0..1> This command will scale the alpha of this world model by the specified value as long as it is flagged as being translucent msg WorldModel ScaleAlpha 0.7
TOGGLE Toggles the ON / OFF state of the WorldModel. msg WorldModel01 TOGGLE;
LOCK Locks the WorldModel. A locked WorldModel may not be activated by a message or by the player. msg WorldModel01 LOCK;
UNLOCK Unlocks the WorldModel so it may be activated through messages or by the player. msg WorldModel01 UNLOCK;
PAUSE Pauses the WorldModel while moving or rotating. Sending a PAUSE message to a WorldModel while is is in the ON or OFF state has no effect. Send a RESUME message to continue the movement or rotation. msg WorldModel01 PAUSE;
RESUME Resumes the movement or rotation from a paused WorldModel. Sending a RESUME message to a WorldModel while it is not paused has no effect. msg WorldModel01 RESUME;
SETPOWERONMULTIPLIER <multiplyer> Setting a power on multiplyer will temporairly increase or decrease the speed at which the WorldModel turns on. This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

KillerMessage This command string is sent to the object that destroys this object. String
