Mass This value sets the mass of the object within the game. Float 2000.000000
SurfaceFlagsOverride This allows the selection a specific surface flag for the object. NOTE: If the Unknown surface flag is used, the surface type of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Unknown
CollisionProperty This allows the selection of an overriding CollisionProperty. If is specified, the surface flag will be used. String (StaticList)
DestroyedFX This allows the selection of a special effect to play when the object is destroyed. If is specified, no effect will be played. String (StaticList)
ShatterType This specifies the type of shattering effect that should be played when the world model is destroyed. This should be set to 'none' if the world model should not shatter String (StaticList)
NeverDestroy Toggles whether the object can be destroyed. Boolean 1.000000
Visible Determines if this object is visible by default Boolean 1.000000
Solid Determines if the object should obstruct movement of other objects Boolean 1.000000
Rayhit Determines if this object can be hit by ray intersection tests Boolean 1.000000
Gravity Determines if gravity should be applied to this object Boolean 0.000000
Translucent Indicates whether or not this world model is translucent. Boolean 0.000000
TranslucentLight Indicates whether or not this world model should use lighting when it is translucent or if it should just be treated as full bright. Boolean 1.000000
CastShadow If true the WorldModel will initially cast a shadow at the LOD specified with the ShadowLOD property. If false the WorldModel will not initially cast a shadow but will save the value of the ShadowLOD property for later use with the CASTSHADOW message. Boolean 1.000000
ShadowLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the shadow for this world model will be visible. For example at Low, this will always show up, at Medium it will only show up in medium and high, and Never will cause the shadow to never be shown. String (StaticList) Low
IsKeyframed Is the WorldModel moved by a keyframer? If it is you must set this flag to true...or life will end as we know it. Boolean 0.000000
RigidBody Should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics? Boolean 0.000000
MPClientOnlyRigidBody In multiplayer games, should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics only on the client? This flag is ignored if RigidBody is false. Boolean 1.000000
StartHidden If this flag is true the WorldModel will be created as if it were sent a HIDDEN 1 message. Boolean 0.000000
Alpha Specifies the alpha of the WorldModel. Float 1.000000
PhysicsShape Indicates what shape will be used to represent this world model in the physics simulation String (StaticList) None
MassKg Indicates the mass of this world model in kilograms Float 1.000000
DensityG Indicates the density of this object measured in grams per cubic centimeter, with 1.0 being the density of normal water. Float 1.100000
Attachments Using this field you can list Objects, Models, and WorldModels that will move with the WorldModel object while maintaining their relative position and rotation. This is commonly used to add Props like door knobs to doors. List all Objects you want attached seperated by a semicolon. Ex. Prop1; RotatingWorldModel2; Prop2; WorldModel1 String
RemoveAttachments If this property is set to true, attachments will be removed (i.e., disappear) when the WorldModel is removed (destroyed). If this property is set to false, the attachments will receive 'destroy' messages and will be destroyed (if they are set up to respond to the destroy message). Boolean 1.000000
AttachDir This is the direction (and magnitude) away from the center of the WorldModel a ray is cast that looks for an object to attach to the WorldModel (when the WorldModel receives an Attach message). Vector 0.000000, 200.000000, 0.000000
Disturbances Properties related to AI disturbances. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
DestroyAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is detroyed. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
StimulusRadius How far away this object is noticeable to AI when disturbed. Float 0.000000
InheritActivationData If True this WorldModel will inherit all activation data from the WorldModel it is attached to. If this WorldModel is not attached to another WorldModel then this property has no effect. If this WorldModel has an ActivationType specified and InheritActivationData is True the ActivationType will be ignored and the ActivationType of the WorldModel this one is attached to will be used instead. Boolean 1.000000
PlayerInteract If true the WorldModel will interact with player. Otherwise it will be non-solid to player. Boolean 1.000000

RotatingWorldModel
A RotatingWorldModel is a WorldModel object that rotates around a specified point.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)

CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)

This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

SlowOn means the object starts moving slowly then picks up pace and will then stay constant. SlowOff will move constantly at first but will slow down at the end of the movement or rotation. Sine starts and ends slowly but looks very smooth and natural. String (StaticList) Linear

GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000
BoxPhysics In the engine, WorldModels have two possible physics models. In the first, the player can walk on and touch every curve and corner of their surface. In the second, the player can only interact with a bounding box that surrounds all the brushes in the WorldModel, just like the box you would get if you selected them in WorldEdit. For geometry with a simple rectangular shape, this is preferred because it's cheaper to calculate. However, for a lot of objects, it's limiting. If you need a player to be able to shoot through the bars in a prison door, you will need BoxPhysics set to FALSE. Boolean 0.000000



SafteyNet
SafteyNet volumes define a space that protect players from fall damage. Player will not recieve fall damage while within a SafteyNet volume.

ScatterVolume
A scatter volume will generate a collection of particles on the geometry contained within the dimensions of the object and will handle rendering these particles at runtime.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)

CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Dims The Dims define the volume an effect takes place in. It is an area defined in WorldEdit units as a box around the center of the effect object. Vector (LocalDims) 128.000000, 128.000000, 128.000000
Density The number of particles placed per 256 square units of surface area. The density can be reduced by placement material blending and clumpiness. Float 128.000000
Clumpiness A number between 0 and 1 that specifies how much particles will 'clump' together. 0 distributes particles evenly over the surface, while 1 will result in very clumpy placement. This works about the same as a 'Noise' material in Max or Maya. Float 0.000000
ClumpSize The approximate dimensions of a clump before it has been modified with the clump cutoff value. Also the approximate distance between clumps. Float 256.000000
ClumpCutoff A number between 0 and 1 that specifies how sharp the edges of clumps should be. 0 will result in a smooth falloff in density towards the edges of the clump, while higher numbers will result in sharper edges and fewer stragglers. Numbers above about 0.7 will result in VERY sparse placement. Float 0.500000
ClumpOffset By default, different scatter volumes will have clumps in the same locations in world space. This can be useful for having multiple materials within the same clump. If you really want the clumps to be independent of each other, change the clump offset in one of the volumes. A good value might be 50 50 50 for example. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Width The base width of the quad that is rendered for each particle. Note that this is independent of material aspect ratio, so if you material is 256x64, you would probably enter a width that is 4 times larger than the height. Float 64.000000
Height The base height of the quad that is rendered for each particle. Note that this is independent of material aspect ratio, so if you material is 256x64, you would probably enter a width that is 4 times larger than the height. Float 64.000000
PlantDepth A value that specifies how far the particle should be embedded in the surface. If this is negative, then the particles will float above the surface. Float 0.000000
Tilt The range of tilt that particles may be placed at. This value is in degrees. Float 30.000000
ScaleRange The +/- range of scales that different particles will have. For example, value of 0.2 will result in particles that are between 80%% and 120%% of the base width and height. Float 0.200000
WaveRate The speed of the wave motion of the particles. This is in degrees per second, so 360 will result in a complete wave cycle every second, while 90 will result in a complete wave cycle every 4 seconds. Float 90.000000
WaveDist The distance in WorldEdit units to move the top of the particles. For example, value of 10 will result in a total movement range of 10 units in either direction. Float 10.000000
WaveSize The approximate dimensions of an area of common movement. Over this area, particles will wave approximately in unison, smoothly blending to other nearby motions. This works about the same as a 'Noise' texture in Max or Maya. Float 128.000000
WaveDirSize The size of areas of similar wind direction. Float 128.000000
MaxDrawDist The maximum distance at which particles in a subvolume of this volume will be visible. Float 1024.000000
MaterialName The material that will be placed on the rendered quad. Particles are placed on the surface based on the bottom center of the quad, so it is usually best for materials to have an anchor point at the bottom center as well. String (Filename)
PlacementMaterial This is an optional material that is only used for placing materials. If this is not empty, then particles will only be placed on polygons that have this material applied to them. If multi-texturing is in use, then the amount of this material will be used to change the density based on vertex alpha. String (Filename)
PlacementCutoff If multi-texturing is in use on a polygon, then points on the surface with a vertex alpha value less than this value will not have any particles placed on them. Float 0.500000
BaseColor The base color of the particles before lighting is added. Color 255.000000, 255.000000, 255.000000
TranslucentLight No lights contribute to the color of the particles, only the base color is used. Boolean 0.000000
Translucent Whether or not the particles that this scatter volume creates are translucent or not. Boolean 1.000000
BackFaces This determines if a back face should be rendered for the scatter particles. This should ONLY be set when using a one sided shader as it slows down rendering Boolean 0.000000
NumImages This indicates the number of images stored in the material. These should be layed out like an image strip along the X axis, so if there are two images, image one sould go from 0-.5, and image two should go from .5-1 horizontally. Float 1.000000

Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
StartOn If true the screen effects will start playing immediately. Boolean 1.000000



SlidingDoor
A SlidingDoor is a Door object that moves a specified distance in a specified direction.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ATTACH <object name(s)> Attaches the object specified in the message

If no object is specified it attaches the first object found in the direction of the AttachDir vector or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0>		 To attach a WorldModel named BOX to a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg Ball (attach box)
DETACH <object name(s)> Detach a specific object attached with the ATTACH message. To detach a WorldModel named BOX from a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg BALL (DETACH BOX)
ATTACHCLASS <class name> This will attach the first object of the specified class found in the direction of AttachDir or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0> To attach any AI to the WorldModel the command would look like:

msg WorldModel (ATTACHCLASS CAI)
DESTROY This command destroys an object in the game as if it had been destroyed trough the loss of all of its hit points. It will play any effects and sounds set up to play at the time of its destruction msg WorldModel DESTROY
NEVERDESTROY <1 or 0> This message allows you to set the NeverDestroy flag through commands. This message does not actually destroy the object but allows destruction if NeverDestroy was set to true initially. msg WorldModel (NEVERDESTROY 1)
ACTIVATE This is an internal message used strictly by the game to activate a WorldModel. Do NOT send any WorldModel an ACTIVATE message. DO NOT USE
RIGIDBODY <bool> This command will set the RigidBody flag on the object making it physically simulated (1) or not (0) msg WorldModel RIGIDBODY 1
SCALEALPHA <0..1> This command will scale the alpha of this world model by the specified value as long as it is flagged as being translucent msg WorldModel ScaleAlpha 0.7
TOGGLE Toggles the ON / OFF state of the WorldModel. msg WorldModel01 TOGGLE;
LOCK Locks the WorldModel. A locked WorldModel may not be activated by a message or by the player. msg WorldModel01 LOCK;
UNLOCK Unlocks the WorldModel so it may be activated through messages or by the player. msg WorldModel01 UNLOCK;
PAUSE Pauses the WorldModel while moving or rotating. Sending a PAUSE message to a WorldModel while is is in the ON or OFF state has no effect. Send a RESUME message to continue the movement or rotation. msg WorldModel01 PAUSE;
RESUME Resumes the movement or rotation from a paused WorldModel. Sending a RESUME message to a WorldModel while it is not paused has no effect. msg WorldModel01 RESUME;
SETPOWERONMULTIPLIER <multiplyer> Setting a power on multiplyer will temporairly increase or decrease the speed at which the WorldModel turns on. This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

DeathCommand This is the command string that is sent when the object has been destroyed. Command

PlayerDamageCommand This is the command string that is sent when the player damages the object. Command
KillerMessage This command string is sent to the object that destroys this object. String

CanRepair Toggles whether the object can be repaired. Boolean 1.000000
CanDamage Toggles whether the object can be damaged. Boolean 1.000000
DamageMask A DamageMask is a list of damage types that are allowed to damage an object they are applied to. Choose none to allow all damage affect this object. Each DamageMask is specified in the database. String (StaticList)
SurfaceFlagsOverride This allows the selection a specific surface flag for the object. NOTE: If the Unknown surface flag is used, the surface type of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Unknown
CollisionProperty This allows the selection of an overriding CollisionProperty. If is specified, the surface flag will be used. String (StaticList)
DestroyedFX This allows the selection of a special effect to play when the object is destroyed. If is specified, no effect will be played. String (StaticList)
ShatterType This specifies the type of shattering effect that should be played when the world model is destroyed. This should be set to 'none' if the world model should not shatter String (StaticList)
Visible Determines if this object is visible by default Boolean 1.000000

Gravity Determines if gravity should be applied to this object Boolean 0.000000
Translucent Indicates whether or not this world model is translucent. Boolean 0.000000
TranslucentLight Indicates whether or not this world model should use lighting when it is translucent or if it should just be treated as full bright. Boolean 1.000000
CastShadow If true the WorldModel will initially cast a shadow at the LOD specified with the ShadowLOD property. If false the WorldModel will not initially cast a shadow but will save the value of the ShadowLOD property for later use with the CASTSHADOW message. Boolean 1.000000
ShadowLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the shadow for this world model will be visible. For example at Low, this will always show up, at Medium it will only show up in medium and high, and Never will cause the shadow to never be shown. String (StaticList) Low
BoxPhysics In the engine, WorldModels have two possible physics models. In the first, the player can walk on and touch every curve and corner of their surface. In the second, the player can only interact with a bounding box that surrounds all the brushes in the WorldModel, just like the box you would get if you selected them in WorldEdit. For geometry with a simple rectangular shape, this is preferred because it's cheaper to calculate. However, for a lot of objects, it's limiting. If you need a player to be able to shoot through the bars in a prison door, you will need BoxPhysics set to FALSE. Boolean 0.000000
IsKeyframed Is the WorldModel moved by a keyframer? If it is you must set this flag to true...or life will end as we know it. Boolean 0.000000
RigidBody Should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics? Boolean 0.000000
MPClientOnlyRigidBody In multiplayer games, should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics only on the client? This flag is ignored if RigidBody is false. Boolean 1.000000
StartHidden If this flag is true the WorldModel will be created as if it were sent a HIDDEN 1 message. Boolean 0.000000
Alpha Specifies the alpha of the WorldModel. Float 1.000000
PhysicsShape Indicates what shape will be used to represent this world model in the physics simulation String (StaticList) None
MassKg Indicates the mass of this world model in kilograms Float 1.000000
DensityG Indicates the density of this object measured in grams per cubic centimeter, with 1.0 being the density of normal water. Float 1.100000
Attachments Using this field you can list Objects, Models, and WorldModels that will move with the WorldModel object while maintaining their relative position and rotation. This is commonly used to add Props like door knobs to doors. List all Objects you want attached seperated by a semicolon. Ex. Prop1; RotatingWorldModel2; Prop2; WorldModel1 String
RemoveAttachments If this property is set to true, attachments will be removed (i.e., disappear) when the WorldModel is removed (destroyed). If this property is set to false, the attachments will receive 'destroy' messages and will be destroyed (if they are set up to respond to the destroy message). Boolean 1.000000
AttachDir This is the direction (and magnitude) away from the center of the WorldModel a ray is cast that looks for an object to attach to the WorldModel (when the WorldModel receives an Attach message). Vector 0.000000, 200.000000, 0.000000
Disturbances Properties related to AI disturbances. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
DestroyAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is detroyed. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
StimulusRadius How far away this object is noticeable to AI when disturbed. Float 0.000000
InheritActivationData If True this WorldModel will inherit all activation data from the WorldModel it is attached to. If this WorldModel is not attached to another WorldModel then this property has no effect. If this WorldModel has an ActivationType specified and InheritActivationData is True the ActivationType will be ignored and the ActivationType of the WorldModel this one is attached to will be used instead. Boolean 1.000000
PlayerInteract If true the WorldModel will interact with player. Otherwise it will be non-solid to player. Boolean 1.000000
Options This is a subset of properties that define some behavior of the Object Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ForceMoveOn If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI when going on. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
ForceMoveOff If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI when going off. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
ActivationType A list of different activatable types used for player interaction. String (StaticList) Default
Sounds This is a subset of properties that define sound behavior and let you specify different sounds to play during different states. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
Commands This is a subset that lets you write commands for specific states that the object will cary out when in that state. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ActivateAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is activated. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
RotateAroundCenter When set to TRUE, object will use the center of worldmodel geometry as rotation point. When sent to FALSE, object will use WorldModel object as rotation point. If RotationPoint is specified, this property is ignored. Boolean 0.000000
PowerOffTime If other than 0.0, sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the On state to the off state. If this is 0.0 then the PowerOnTime value is used. Float 0.000000
PowerOffRadius If other than 0.0, sets the minimum distance in centimeters from the WorldModels's power off position that ALL characters must be for the WorldModel to power off. Float 0.000000
Mass This value sets the mass of the object within the game. Float 10000.000000
NeverDestroy Toggles whether the object can be destroyed. Boolean 1.000000
PlayerActivate If TRUE the player can directly interact with this object by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
AIActivate If TRUE this lets the AI know they can interact with this object. When FALSE the AI will treat the object like it doesn't exist. Boolean 1.000000
StartOpen When set to true the Door will be opening as soon as the game loads. Boolean 0.000000
TriggerClose If this is set to FALSE the player can not directly close the Door by pressing use. The Door can however be closed by a message from another object like a switch. If set to TRUE the player can directly close the Door by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
RemainOpen If set to FALSE the Door will try to start closing as soon as it becomes fully open. If TRUE the Door will stay open untill told to close, either by the player or a message from another object. Boolean 1.000000
ForceMove If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
Locked When set to TRUE the object starts in a Locked state. It can't be activated or triggered by a message unless it is unlocked. To unlock an object send it an UNLOCK message. To lock it again send a LOCK message. Boolean 0.000000
Waveform A list of predefined wave types for movement. Linear is a constant rate, objects will move at the same rate throught its whole path or rotation. SlowOn means the object starts moving slowly then picks up pace and will then stay constant. SlowOff will move constantly at first but will slow down at the end of the movement or rotation. Sine starts and ends slowly but looks very smooth and natural. String (StaticList) Linear
OpeningSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door starts opening. String (Filename)
OpenSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door is fully opened. String (Filename)
ClosingSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the Door starts closing. String (Filename)
ClosedSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object is fully closed. String (Filename)
LockedSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this sound will begin to play. String (Filename)
SoundPos The position that the sounds will be played from, relative to the objects position. If this is (0.0 0.0 0.0) the sounds will play at the center of the object, (0.0 25.0 0.0) will place the sounds 25 units above the objects center. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
SoundRadius This is the extent of the sounds, they will not be heard beyond this distance from the SoundPos. Float (Radius) 1000.000000
LoopSounds When set to TRUE, the sounds will comtinue to loop untill they change state. When FALSE the sounds will play their full length once and will then be destroyed. Boolean 0.000000
OpenCommand A command that this Door will execute when it is fully open. Command
ClosedCommand A command that this Door will execue when it is fully closed. Command
OpeningCommand A command that this Door will execute when starting to open. Command
ClosingCommand A command that this Door will execute when starting to close. Command
LockedCommand If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this command will be executed. Command
MoveDir This is the direction of movement this object will go when turned on. This is relative to the objects local coordinates so a MoveDir of (0.0 1.0 0.0) will always move in the objects positive Y direction. Vector 0.000000, 1.000000, 0.000000
MoveDist This is the distance the object will move in the direction specified in MoveDir. Float 64.000000
OpeningTime Sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the Off state to the on state. Float 1.000000
ClosingTime If other than 0.0, sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the On state to the off state. If this is 0.0 then the OpeningTime value is used. Float 0.000000
MoveDelay Amount of delay in seconds between the time the WorldModel is triggered and when it begins its movement. Float 0.000000
OpenWaitTime Amount of time in seconds that the Door will remain open before automatically closing, and the amount of time before the Door can be triggered again. Float 0.000000
CloseWaitTime Amount of time in secomds before the Door can be opened after being closed. Float 0.000000
DoorLink Use this to link two Doors together that you would like to open at the same time (i.e., Door1's DoorLink would be Door2, and Door2's DoorLink would be Door1). NOTE--Only the opening of linked doors is supported. Each door may be closed individually. String
Sector1 The brush name of a sector that will be turned on and off by this door as it opens and closes. String
Sector2 The brush name of a sector that will be turned on and off by this door as it opens and closes. String
GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000

ShadowLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the shadow for this world model will be visible. For example at Low, this will always show up, at Medium it will only show up in medium and high, and Never will cause the shadow to never be shown. String (StaticList) Low
BoxPhysics In the engine, WorldModels have two possible physics models. In the first, the player can walk on and touch every curve and corner of their surface. In the second, the player can only interact with a bounding box that surrounds all the brushes in the WorldModel, just like the box you would get if you selected them in WorldEdit. For geometry with a simple rectangular shape, this is preferred because it's cheaper to calculate. However, for a lot of objects, it's limiting. If you need a player to be able to shoot through the bars in a prison door, you will need BoxPhysics set to FALSE. Boolean 0.000000
IsKeyframed Is the WorldModel moved by a keyframer? If it is you must set this flag to true...or life will end as we know it. Boolean 0.000000
RigidBody Should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics? Boolean 0.000000
MPClientOnlyRigidBody In multiplayer games, should this world model be simulated with rigid body physics only on the client? This flag is ignored if RigidBody is false. Boolean 1.000000
StartHidden If this flag is true the WorldModel will be created as if it were sent a HIDDEN 1 message. Boolean 0.000000
Alpha Specifies the alpha of the WorldModel. Float 1.000000
PhysicsShape Indicates what shape will be used to represent this world model in the physics simulation String (StaticList) None
MassKg Indicates the mass of this world model in kilograms Float 1.000000
DensityG Indicates the density of this object measured in grams per cubic centimeter, with 1.0 being the density of normal water. Float 1.100000
Attachments Using this field you can list Objects, Models, and WorldModels that will move with the WorldModel object while maintaining their relative position and rotation. This is commonly used to add Props like door knobs to doors. List all Objects you want attached seperated by a semicolon. Ex. Prop1; RotatingWorldModel2; Prop2; WorldModel1 String
RemoveAttachments If this property is set to true, attachments will be removed (i.e., disappear) when the WorldModel is removed (destroyed). If this property is set to false, the attachments will receive 'destroy' messages and will be destroyed (if they are set up to respond to the destroy message). Boolean 1.000000
AttachDir This is the direction (and magnitude) away from the center of the WorldModel a ray is cast that looks for an object to attach to the WorldModel (when the WorldModel receives an Attach message). Vector 0.000000, 200.000000, 0.000000
Disturbances Properties related to AI disturbances. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
DestroyAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is detroyed. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
StimulusRadius How far away this object is noticeable to AI when disturbed. Float 0.000000
InheritActivationData If True this WorldModel will inherit all activation data from the WorldModel it is attached to. If this WorldModel is not attached to another WorldModel then this property has no effect. If this WorldModel has an ActivationType specified and InheritActivationData is True the ActivationType will be ignored and the ActivationType of the WorldModel this one is attached to will be used instead. Boolean 1.000000
PlayerInteract If true the WorldModel will interact with player. Otherwise it will be non-solid to player. Boolean 1.000000
Options This is a subset of properties that define some behavior of the Object Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ForceMoveOn If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI when going on. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
ForceMoveOff If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI when going off. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
ActivationType A list of different activatable types used for player interaction. String (StaticList) Default
Sounds This is a subset of properties that define sound behavior and let you specify different sounds to play during different states. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
Commands This is a subset that lets you write commands for specific states that the object will cary out when in that state. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ActivateAlarmLevel How alarming it is to the AI when this object is activated. Corresponds to thresholds in AIBrains in aibutes.txt. Integer 0.000000
RotateAroundCenter When set to TRUE, object will use the center of worldmodel geometry as rotation point. When sent to FALSE, object will use WorldModel object as rotation point. If RotationPoint is specified, this property is ignored. Boolean 0.000000
PowerOffRadius If other than 0.0, sets the minimum distance in centimeters from the WorldModels's power off position that ALL characters must be for the WorldModel to power off. Float 0.000000
PlayerActivate If TRUE the player can directly interact with this object by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
AIActivate If TRUE this lets the AI know they can interact with this object. When FALSE the AI will treat the object like it doesn't exist. Boolean 1.000000
StartOn When set to TRUE the object will be turnning on as soon as the game loads. Boolean 0.000000
TriggerOff If this is set to FALSE the player can not directly turn the object off by pressing use. The object can however be turned off by a message from another object like a switch. If set to TRUE the player can directly turn off or close the object by pressing use. Boolean 1.000000
RemainOn If this is FALSE the Object will start turnning itself off or close as soon as it turns on or opens. If TRUE the object will stay on or open untill told to turn off, either by the player or a message. Boolean 1.000000
ForceMove If set to TRUE, the object will not be stopped by the player or AI. It will continue on its path like there is nothing in the way. Boolean 0.000000
Locked When set to TRUE the object starts in a Locked state. It can't be activated or triggered by a message unless it is unlocked. To unlock an object send it an UNLOCK message. To lock it again send a LOCK message. Boolean 0.000000
Waveform A list of predefined wave types for movement. Linear is a constant rate, objects will move at the same rate throught its whole path or rotation. SlowOn means the object starts moving slowly then picks up pace and will then stay constant. SlowOff will move constantly at first but will slow down at the end of the movement or rotation. Sine starts and ends slowly but looks very smooth and natural. String (StaticList) Linear
PowerOnSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object starts to turn on. String (Filename)
OnSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object is fully turned on. String (Filename)
PowerOffSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object starts to turn off. String (Filename)
OffSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. This sound will begin playing as soon as the object is fully turned off. String (Filename)
LockedSound The path of any .wav file can be entered here. If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this sound will begin to play. String (Filename)
SoundPos The position that the sounds will be played from, relative to the objects position. If this is (0.0 0.0 0.0) the sounds will play at the center of the object, (0.0 25.0 0.0) will place the sounds 25 units above the objects center. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
SoundRadius This is the extent of the sounds, they will not be heard beyond this distance from the SoundPos. Float (Radius) 1000.000000
LoopSounds When set to TRUE, the sounds will comtinue to loop untill they change state. When FALSE the sounds will play their full length once and will then be destroyed. Boolean 0.000000
OnCommand A command that this object will execute when it is fully on. Command
OffCommand A command that this object will execue when it is fully off. Command
PowerOnCommand A command that this object will execute when starting to turn on. Command
PowerOffCommand A command that this object will execute when starting to turn off. Command
LockedCommand If this object is locked and the player or another object tries to activate it, this command will be executed. Command
MoveDir This is the direction of movement this object will go when turned on. This is relative to the objects local coordinates so a MoveDir of (0.0 1.0 0.0) will always move in the objects positive Y direction. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 1.000000
MoveDist This is the distance the object will move in the direction specified in MoveDir. Float 8.000000
PowerOnTime Sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the Off state to the on state. Float 1.000000
PowerOffTime If other than 0.0, sets the time in seconds for how long it takes the WorldModel to go from the On state to the off state. If this is 0.0 then the PowerOnTime value is used. Float 0.000000
MoveDelay Amount of delay in seconds between the time the WorldModel is triggered and when it begins its movement. Float 0.000000
OnWaitTime Amount of time in seconds that the WorldModel will remain on before turnning off automatically, and the amount of time before the WorldModel can be triggered on again. Float 0.000000
OffWaitTime Amount of time in secomds before the WorldModel can be turned on after being turned off. Float 0.000000
GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000



SlidingWorldModel
A SlidingWorldModel is a WorldModel object that moves a specified distance in a specified direction.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ATTACH <object name(s)> Attaches the object specified in the message

If no object is specified it attaches the first object found in the direction of the AttachDir vector or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0>		 To attach a WorldModel named BOX to a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg Ball (attach box)
DETACH <object name(s)> Detach a specific object attached with the ATTACH message. To detach a WorldModel named BOX from a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg BALL (DETACH BOX)
ATTACHCLASS <class name> This will attach the first object of the specified class found in the direction of AttachDir or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0> To attach any AI to the WorldModel the command would look like:

msg WorldModel (ATTACHCLASS CAI)
DESTROY This command destroys an object in the game as if it had been destroyed trough the loss of all of its hit points. It will play any effects and sounds set up to play at the time of its destruction msg WorldModel DESTROY
NEVERDESTROY <1 or 0> This message allows you to set the NeverDestroy flag through commands. This message does not actually destroy the object but allows destruction if NeverDestroy was set to true initially. msg WorldModel (NEVERDESTROY 1)
ACTIVATE This is an internal message used strictly by the game to activate a WorldModel. Do NOT send any WorldModel an ACTIVATE message. DO NOT USE
RIGIDBODY <bool> This command will set the RigidBody flag on the object making it physically simulated (1) or not (0) msg WorldModel RIGIDBODY 1
SCALEALPHA <0..1> This command will scale the alpha of this world model by the specified value as long as it is flagged as being translucent msg WorldModel ScaleAlpha 0.7
TOGGLE Toggles the ON / OFF state of the WorldModel. msg WorldModel01 TOGGLE;
LOCK Locks the WorldModel. A locked WorldModel may not be activated by a message or by the player. msg WorldModel01 LOCK;
UNLOCK Unlocks the WorldModel so it may be activated through messages or by the player. msg WorldModel01 UNLOCK;
PAUSE Pauses the WorldModel while moving or rotating. Sending a PAUSE message to a WorldModel while is is in the ON or OFF state has no effect. Send a RESUME message to continue the movement or rotation. msg WorldModel01 PAUSE;
RESUME Resumes the movement or rotation from a paused WorldModel. Sending a RESUME message to a WorldModel while it is not paused has no effect. msg WorldModel01 RESUME;
SETPOWERONMULTIPLIER <multiplyer> Setting a power on multiplyer will temporairly increase or decrease the speed at which the WorldModel turns on. This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

SnowVolume
SnowVolumes are used to define a spatial area where snow particles will be created and fall towards the ground.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ON This message turns the snow effect on. The effect will turn on through precipitation of particles from the top of the volume msg SnowVolume ON
OFF This message turns the particle system off. The particles disappear immediately msg SnowVolume OFF


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Dims The Dims define the volume an effect takes place in. It is an area defined in WorldEdit units as a box around the center of the effect object. Vector (Dims) 128.000000, 128.000000, 128.000000
Density The number of particles placed per 256 cubic units of volume. Snow volumes with different dimensions (vertical and XZ) but with the same density can be seemlessly placed next to each other since the density is relative to the volume and doesn't represent a specific number of particles. Float 512.000000
ParticleRadius The approximate radius of a particle in WorldEdit units. Float 1.000000
FallRate The speed at which snow will fall in WorldEdit units per second. A value of 0 will result in particles that don't fall, but may still spin. Negative values will not generate desirable results. Float 80.000000
TumbleRate The number of degrees of rotation per second around a central point. Float 180.000000
TumbleRadius The distance from the base particle position to rotate at. 0 will result in particles that fall straight down, 10 will result in particles that flutter up to 10 units in either direction as they fall. Float 5.000000
MaxDrawDist The maximum distance at which particles are drawn. Starting at about 80%% of this distance, particles will begin to fade out. Float 1024.000000
BaseColor The base color of the particles before lighting is added. Color 255.000000, 255.000000, 255.000000
TranslucentLight No lights contribute to the color of the particles, only the base color is used. Boolean 0.000000
Translucent Whether or not the particles that this scatter volume creates are translucent or not. Boolean 1.000000
BackFaces This determines if a back face should be rendered for the scatter particles. This should ONLY be set when using a one sided shader as it slows down rendering Boolean 0.000000
MaterialName The material to render the particles with. All of the mip levels need to have a black border at the top and right edges of the material in order to render correctly. The material needs to use non-premultiplied alpha (for example, entirely white color channel, with the actual shape in the alpha channel.) String (Filename)
StartOn Should the SnowVolume start emitting snow when it is created? Boolean 1.000000

SoundFX
SoundFX objects are used to play a specific sound file at a specific position in the database.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)

Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
StartOn This flag toggles the sound to start in the on state. Boolean 1.000000
Sound The path to any .wav file, or a sound database entry, may be entered here. This sound file will be played when the SoundFX object is triggered on. String (Filename)
Priority You can assign Priority values to SoundFX objects so that some sounds will take priority over others. The valid values are 0, 1, and 2. Lower numbers have lower priority. Integer 1.000000
OuterRadius See InnerRadius. Float (Radius) 500.000000
InnerRadius It's useful and simple to give a sound two radii, one Inner where it plays at full Volume, and one Outer where it plays at a reduced volume. It's a cheap way of having a sound fade over distance without requiring possibly expensive audio processing in-game. The values a set in WorldEdit units. Float (Radius) 100.000000
Volume This value is expressed as a percentage. It is how loud the sound is at its origin point. Integer 100.000000
PitchShift This value speeds up or slows down the file. You can set a different pitch with this property to make it play lower or higher in pitch. 1.00 is normal pitch, 1.10 would be pitched up 10%, 0.90 would be 10% pitched down. It does this by changing the playback sample rate of the file. Float 1.000000
Ambient Setting Ambient to TRUE means that the sound will play as if it were coming from everywhere around you, but will get quieter as you move farther away from it. Setting Ambient to FALSE means that the sound will play from a specific point. Boolean 1.000000
Loop This flag toogles whether the sound will loop continuously or play only once when triggered on. Boolean 1.000000
PlayAttached Setting this flag to true will allow its origin point to move. This flag is useful if the sound is to be attached to a moving object. Boolean 0.000000
Filter Every sound played in FEAR may have some type of software filtering done to it before it is passed off to the sound card. The current implementation allows sounds to independently specify what filter they use when they are played, or (by default) use the 'dynamic' filter associated with the current listener (camera) position. Also sounds can specify that they do not want to be filtered. String (StaticList) UnFiltered
MixChannel This is the mixer channel for the sound effect. Putting -1 will use the sound class's default value. Integer 1.000000
DopplerFactor This is Doppler multiplier. 1 is default (no change), and 0 turns off Doppler. Float 1.000000
UseOcclusion Setting this flag to control the type of occlusion. 'No Inner Radius' means no occlusion inside the inner radius. (3D sounds only). String (StaticList) Full
VolumeFade Setting VolumeFade to TRUE means that the sound can be controlled by VOLUME messages. This is for optimization so only set for sounds you need to do this to. Boolean 0.000000
GlobalResources Indicates whether the object's resources should be considered as global in the resource streaming system. Boolean 0.000000

COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
ATTACH <object name(s)> Attaches the object specified in the message

If no object is specified it attaches the first object found in the direction of the AttachDir vector or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0>		 To attach a WorldModel named BOX to a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg Ball (attach box)
DETACH <object name(s)> Detach a specific object attached with the ATTACH message. To detach a WorldModel named BOX from a WorldModel named BALL, the command would look like:

msg BALL (DETACH BOX)
ATTACHCLASS <class name> This will attach the first object of the specified class found in the direction of AttachDir or within the dimensions of the world model if AttachDir is <0,0,0> To attach any AI to the WorldModel the command would look like:

msg WorldModel (ATTACHCLASS CAI)
DESTROY This command destroys an object in the game as if it had been destroyed trough the loss of all of its hit points. It will play any effects and sounds set up to play at the time of its destruction msg WorldModel DESTROY
NEVERDESTROY <1 or 0> This message allows you to set the NeverDestroy flag through commands. This message does not actually destroy the object but allows destruction if NeverDestroy was set to true initially. msg WorldModel (NEVERDESTROY 1)
ACTIVATE This is an internal message used strictly by the game to activate a WorldModel. Do NOT send any WorldModel an ACTIVATE message. DO NOT USE
RIGIDBODY <bool> This command will set the RigidBody flag on the object making it physically simulated (1) or not (0) msg WorldModel RIGIDBODY 1
SCALEALPHA <0..1> This command will scale the alpha of this world model by the specified value as long as it is flagged as being translucent msg WorldModel ScaleAlpha 0.7
TOGGLE Toggles the ON / OFF state of the WorldModel. msg WorldModel01 TOGGLE;
LOCK Locks the WorldModel. A locked WorldModel may not be activated by a message or by the player. msg WorldModel01 LOCK;
UNLOCK Unlocks the WorldModel so it may be activated through messages or by the player. msg WorldModel01 UNLOCK;
PAUSE Pauses the WorldModel while moving or rotating. Sending a PAUSE message to a WorldModel while is is in the ON or OFF state has no effect. Send a RESUME message to continue the movement or rotation. msg WorldModel01 PAUSE;
RESUME Resumes the movement or rotation from a paused WorldModel. Sending a RESUME message to a WorldModel while it is not paused has no effect. msg WorldModel01 RESUME;
SETPOWERONMULTIPLIER <multiplyer> Setting a power on multiplyer will temporairly increase or decrease the speed at which the WorldModel turns on. This is off a base multiplyer of 1 and it will be reset after the first time the WorldModel turns on after setting a multiplyer. Use the ON and OFF with the optional time value for more precise control. msg WorldModel01 (SETPOWERONMULTIPLYER 0.5); Setting the multiplyer to 0.5 will enable the WorldModel to take twice as long to reach the ON state.
CANACTIVATE <1 or 0> Enables or disables the players ability to activate the WorldModel using the action key msg WorldModel01 (CANACTIVATE 0);
SETSTARTINGANGLES <X> <Y> <Z> Allows you to set the WorldModel's StartingAngles via a message msg WorldModel01 (SETSTARTINGANGLES 0 15 0);
ON [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel on. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the on state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel on using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 ON;

To turn a WorldModel on over 2 seconds in a linear movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (ON 2.0 Linear);
OFF [time] [waveform] Turn the WorldModel off. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the off state. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. To turn the WorldModel off using default values the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 OFF;

To turn a WorldModel off over half a second in a sine wave movement, the command would look like:

msg WorldModel01 (OFF 0.5 Sine);
ROTATE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Rotate the WorldModel to the specified angle around each axis. All angles are in degrees and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to reach the angles. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (ROTATE 0 -15 0 2.5 SlowOn);
MOVE <X> <Y> <Z> [time] [waveform] Move the WorldModel the specified distance along each axis. All distances are in centimeters and relative to the off position of the WorldModel. The optional parameter [time] is the seconds it takes for the WorldModel to move the distance. Valid values for the optional parameter [waveform] are: Linear, Sine, SlowOn and SlowOff. msg WorldModel01 (MOVE -100 50 0 0.5 Linear);

BoxPhysics In the engine, WorldModels have two possible physics models. In the first, the player can walk on and touch every curve and corner of their surface. In the second, the player can only interact with a bounding box that surrounds all the brushes in the WorldModel, just like the box you would get if you selected them in WorldEdit. For geometry with a simple rectangular shape, this is preferred because it's cheaper to calculate. However, for a lot of objects, it's limiting. If you need a player to be able to shoot through the bars in a prison door, you will need BoxPhysics set to FALSE. Boolean 0.000000

StartupCommand
StartupCommand objects are used to send a command immediately when the level loads for the first time.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)

CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)

Trigger
Trigger objects are used to send a number of commands when the player touches the trigger or through controlled activation by sending the trigger an ON message.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)
HIDDEN <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible, solid, and rayhit. msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (HIDDEN 0)
REMOVE Removes the object from the game permanently. msg <ObjectName> REMOVE
CASTSHADOW <bool> Toggles whether the object casts a shadow. msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (CASTSHADOW 0)
SETPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Sets the position of an object. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
MOVETOPOS <X> <Y> <Z> DEBUGGING ONLY. Moves to the position, with collisions. msg <ObjectName> (MOVETOPOS 50.5 100 75)
SETROTATION <yaw> <pitch> <roll> DEBUGGING ONLY. Rotates object to euler angles. msg <ObjectName> (SETROTATION 90.0 0 0)
COPYXFORM <object> DEBUGGING ONLY. Copies trasform of <object> to this object. msg <ObjectName> (COPYXFORM ThePoint)
LOCK Locks the Trigger so that it ignores all commands other than UNLOCK and REMOVE and cannot be activated by the player msg Trigger LOCK
UNLOCK Unlocks the Trigger msg Trigger UNLOCK
ON Tells the object to send its commands msg Trigger ON
TEAM <0, 1, -1> Specifies which team can activate this trigger msg Trigger (TEAM 1)


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Dims The dimensions of the trigger in the game. If the player has to walk into the trigger to fire it, you should set the dimensions. If the trigger is fired off by another object, then they don't need to be changed. Trigger dimensions are set as x, y and z values. You can make each of them as small as 0 or as large as you need. For example, for a trigger that fills a typical doorway you would set the dims to 128 128 4. Using the 4 is just to make the object easier to find. Triggers can be any size. Vector (Dims) 16.000000, 16.000000, 16.000000
NumberOfActivations This value sets how many times the Trigger object can be activated. Setting this value to 0 allows the Trigger to be activated an infinite number of times. Integer 1.000000
SendDelay A specified amount of seconds between the time the Trigger object receives a trigger message, and the when it sends its command strings. Float 0.000000
TriggerDelay After being triggered, this is the amount of time before the Trigger object can be activated again. Float 0.000000
Commands This is a subset of properties that are command strings the trigger object will process when triggered. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
Command1 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command2 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command3 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command4 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command5 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command6 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command7 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command8 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command9 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
Command10 These are the command strings that will be sent. Command
PlayerTriggerable This flag toggles whether or not the players bounding box intersecting that of the Trigger will activate it. Boolean 1.000000
AITriggerable This flag toggles whether or not an AIs bounding box intersecting that of the Trigger will activate it. Boolean 0.000000
AITriggerName Triggers that are set to be AI triggerable can be set up to only respond to a specific AI. Enter the name of the specific AI that you want to activate the trigger in this field. String
TimedTrigger If this flag is set to true the Trigger object will continue to send its messages repeatedly based on the minimum and maximum times set in the MinTriggerTime and MaxTriggerTime fields. Boolean 0.000000
MinTriggerTime If the trigger's TimedTrigger flag is set to true, this value will set the shortest delay before the trigger fires. Float 0.000000
MaxTriggerTime If the trigger's TimedTrigger flag is set to true, this value will set the longest delay before the trigger fires. Float 10.000000
ActivationCount This field is used to set an activation threshold. The Trigger object will need to receive a number of 'trigger' messages equal to the value entered in this field before its messages will be sent. Integer 1.000000
Locked This property can be used if you only want to be able to trip the trigger after a certain event has happened. You would also need a Condition variable, or Unlock messages on the objects that can unlock the trigger. Boolean 0.000000
ActivationSound Specifies a sound file to play when the trigger fires. If you want a player to know that they've just set something off, found a clue or entered a cut scene, this can be useful. String (Filename)
SoundRadius Determines the distance from the trigger that you can hear the ActivationSound play, if it has one. Float (Radius) 200.000000
AttachToObject Attaches a Trigger to an object, such as a Prop or a WorldModel. If the object moves, so does the trigger. String
HUDLookAtDist If this is greater than 0, a HUD icon indicating that the player is close to the trigger will appear when the player is looking at the trigger and is this distancs away from the dims of the object. Float (Radius) -1.000000
HUDAlwaysOnDist If this is greater than 0, a HUD icon indicating that the player is close to the trigger will appear when the player is this distance away form the center of the object. Float (Radius) -1.000000
TriggerType A dropdown list of 'TriggerTypes' from TriggerTypes.txt. Selecting a TriggerType will display the icon specified in the text file when the player is within the HUDLookAtDist and HUDAlwaysOnDist. Selecting will display no icon. String (StaticList)
Team This is a dropdown that allows you to set which team can activate this trigger while playing a team game. String (StaticList) NoTeam

VolumeBrush
VolumeBrushes allow spaces to be defined that have different movement and physics properties than the default physics and movement.

Message Description Example
VISIBLE <bool> Toggles whether the object is visible. msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (VISIBLE 0)
SOLID <bool> Toggles whether the object is solid. msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 1)<BR>msg <ObjectName> (SOLID 0)

ON Enables the effects associated with the volume msg VolumeBrush ON
OFF Disables the effects associated with the volume msg VolumeBrush OFF


Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Rotation The orientation of this object represented by euler angles in degrees Rotation 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Template Indicates that this object will not exist at runtime, and may be used as an object template for Spawner objects Boolean 0.000000
IsGore Indicates that this object is gory and should not exist for low-violence clients. Boolean 0.000000
ObjectLOD This value indicates at which detail levels the object will exist. For example at Low, this object will always exist, at Medium it will only exist in medium and high detail, and Never will cause the object to never exist. String (StaticList) Low
Visible Determines if this object is visible by default Boolean 0.000000
Hidden This flag allows you to make a volume begin hidden in the level. Later you can send a (hidden 0) message to the VolumeBrush object to unhide it. Boolean 0.000000
Resistance This value affects the resistance of the players movement through the volume. Float 0.000000
Friction This property allows you to alter the friction coefficient of surfaces to create slippery surfaces. Float 1.000000
Current This is a force that pushes against the player. Use positive or negative values along each axis (x, y, and z) to indicate the direction and strength of the current. In general, you'll need values in the thousands in order to lift a player off the ground. This works well to create moving streams or areas of rushing wind. Vector 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
Damage Sets amount of damage dealt by this area for every second the player is in it. Float 0.000000
DamageType This is a dropdown menu that allows you to choose the damage type that will be inflicted by the Volume. String (StaticList) CHOKE
TintColor You can define a tint for the player's view if you want the area to look as if it's filled with light or liquid. Color 255.000000, 255.000000, 255.000000
LightAdd This allows you to further alter the view from inside a Volume. Color 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
SoundFilter You could have sound behave differently inside the volume. In the case of liquid, you could mute out high frequencies. In the case of a dimensional gate, you might add a strange echo or other filter. String (StaticList) Dynamic
CanPlayMovementSounds This flag disables the footstep sounds and head-bob motion in a volume. Boolean 1.000000
FogStuff This is a subset of properties that define the fog effects that will be seen when the player is within the Volume Brush. Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
FogEnable This flag toggles the fog effects on and off. Boolean 0.000000
FogFarZ This is a value that determines at what distance the fog reaches full saturation. Float 300.000000
FogNearZ This value determines at what distance the fog is at zero saturation. Float -100.000000
FogColor This color picker determines the color of the fog effect. Color 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
ForceVolumeProps This is a subset of properties that define the physics force volume that can be associated with this volume to control how rigid bodies are affected in this volume Integer (GroupOwner) 0.000000
ForceVolume Determines if this volume brush should have a force volume associated with it or not Boolean 0.000000
ForceDir This specifies the direction of the constant force in the volume, relative to the volume Rotation 270.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
ForceMag This specifies the strength of the constant force, and can range from 0 to +inf Float 100.000000
ForceWaveFreq This is used to control the fluctuation of the constant force, and describes how many times per second the force will cycle between +1 and -1. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 0.500000
ForceWaveAmp This is used to control the how much the fluctuation of the wave influences the scale of the force. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
ForceWaveBaseOffset The is used to control the base offset for the wave fluctuation of the scale. The full formula is sin(Time / Frequency) * Amplitude + Base Float 1.000000
Density This is used to specify the density of the volume. Setting this to zero will disable buoyancy, anything else will cause the volume to apply a force based upon how dense this liquid is and how large the objects inside of it are. This is in g/cm^3. The density of water is 1 g/cm^3 Float 1.000000
LinearDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it moves through the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.002000
AngularDrag This is used to specify how much drag is introduced on an object as it rotates in the water. The higher this value, the more drag incurred. This is scaled based upon the speed of the object and how much surface area the object has in the water. Float 0.300000
SurfaceFlagsOverride This dropdown menu allows you to choose a specific surface flag for the VolumeBrush. NOTE: If the Unknown surface flag is used, the surface flag of the material applied to the brush will be used. String (StaticList) Unknown
RayHit This flag toggles whether or not the object will be rayhit. Boolean 0.000000
StartOn This flag toggles whether or not the volume will be considered ON when the level first loads. Boolean 1.000000

Property Description Type Default
Name The name of this object String noname
Pos The position in the world of this object. Vector (Distance) 0.000000, 0.000000, 0.000000
